[38;5;129m│[0m The vulnerability is a straightforward OS command injection. The application [38;5;129m│[0m
[38;5;129m│[0m likely constructs a shell command like `curl -I <user_input>` or similar to  [38;5;129m│[0m
[38;5;129m│[0m check the URL status. By injecting `; ls #`, the command becomes something   [38;5;129m│[0m
[38;5;129m│[0m like `curl -I http://example.com; ls #` where the hash comments out the      [38;5;129m│[0m
[38;5;129m│[0m rest. The command output is captured and embedded into the JSON message      [38;5;129m│[0m
[38;5;129m│[0m field. Backtick injection fails because the backticks are likely URL-encoded [38;5;129m│[0m
[38;5;129m│[0m or the shell interprets them differently in this context. The key insight is [38;5;129m│[0m
[38;5;129m│[0m that the output appears between the HTTP status code (200) and the word      [38;5;129m│[0m
[38;5;129m│[0m "status" in the message string, which allowed extraction of the flag file    [38;5;129m│[0m
[38;5;129m│[0m content directly.                                                            [38;5;129m│[0m
